    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 29,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "First-order perturbation theory assumes the atom never leaves the ground state. It keeps draining the ground state as if it were full — even after it has emptied.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.05,
      "build": {
        "status": "SLATE",
        "src": null,
        "filled_by": null,
        "at": "2026-07-16T10:27:19",
        "needs": "PIPELINE → render animated_graphics.py scene B04_*"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 40,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "So the formula integrates indefinitely, producing a probability that climbs as a parabola — past one, past two, with no ceiling.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.96,
      "build": {
        "status": "SLATE",
        "src": null,
        "filled_by": null,
        "at": "2026-07-16T10:27:19",
        "needs": "PIPELINE → render animated_graphics.py scene B05_*"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 50,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "The exact two-level solution — Rabi's formula — accounts for the ground state emptying. The probability becomes a sine: it climbs to one, then the atom flips back.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.56,
      "build": {
        "status": "SLATE",
        "src": null,
        "filled_by": null,
        "at": "2026-07-16T10:27:19",
        "needs": "PIPELINE → render animated_graphics.py scene B06_*"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 62,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Parabola and sine agree when the product of coupling times time is small — early, weak-drive limit. They diverge as that product approaches pi.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.55,
